data.content:
Dirty Air Filter
A maintenance issue causing reduced airflow and cooling efficiency.

Low Refrigerant
A system failure due to insufficient refrigerant, potentially caused by leaks.

Faulty Capacitor
An electrical component failure affecting the AC unit's ability to start or run properly.

data.entity_name: AC Unit Will Not Turn On
data.content:
AC Unit Will Not Turn On
An event where the AC unit fails to activate despite proper thermostat settings.

No Power to Unit
An electrical issue causing the AC unit to remain inactive.

Faulty Thermostat
A control system failure leading to improper communication between the thermostat and the AC unit.

Failed Transformer
An electrical component failure affecting power supply within the AC system.

data.entity_name: AC is Making a Loud Noise
data.content:
AC is Making a Loud Noise
An event where the AC unit emits unusual noises, indicating potential mechanical or electrical issues.

Transformer
A Transformer is a device used in power distribution systems to step up or step down voltage levels. It is critical for ensuring proper power supply to devices.

AC Unit
An AC Unit refers to an air conditioning system, which can include both indoor and outdoor components responsible for cooling and heating spaces.

Fan
A Fan is a mechanical device used in AC units to circulate air, typically part of the condenser or blower system.

Blower Wheel
The Blower Wheel is an internal component of the AC unit's indoor section, responsible for distributing conditioned air throughout the space.

Refrigerant Lines
Refrigerant Lines are pipes that circulate refrigerant through the AC system to facilitate heat transfer and cooling.
